UNICEF Sanitation Report

Author

Eva Bouchard

Global Access to Sanitation and Development Indicators

Access to improved sanitation is more than a question of infrastructure its a reflection of development, education, and health systems.

In this report, we examine:

  • The global distribution of sanitation access
  • The top and bottom-performing countries
  • Correlations with two key development metrics:
    • GDP per capita
    • Life expectancy at birth
  • Trends over time in selected countries

Data comes from UNICEFs sanitation indicators and supporting metadata.

Global Sanitation Inequality World Map

The map displays the percentage of the population without access to improved sanitation facilities in each country.

  • Darker shades indicate better access
  • Data is based on the year 2020

Key insights: - Sub-Saharan Africa shows the highest concentration of countries with poor access. - Parts of South Asia also face critical sanitation challenges. - This map highlights global disparities and the urgency to improve sanitation infrastructure, aligned with SDG 6 (Clean Water and Sanitation for All).

Public Health Insight

Countries with the lowest life expectancy also tend to have limited access to sanitation infrastructure.
This highlights that sanitation is not just a utility its a critical pillar of public health and social equity.

Where Money Flows, Sanitation Follows

Poverty fuels the sanitation gap

Countries with GDP per capita below 5000 show an average sanitation access of less than 50%, while those above $40,000 maintain near-universal coverage.

This striking divide highlights the direct link between economic development and basic human rights like access to clean sanitation.

Life Expectancy and Sanitation Access

This scatter plot shows the relationship between life expectancy and the percentage of the population without access to improved sanitation.

  • Each dot represents a country-year data point.
  • The strong negative correlation indicates that longer life expectancy is associated with better sanitation access.
  • The regression line further reinforces this link.

Key insights: - Countries with a life expectancy below 60 years often have very poor sanitation access, with many data points clustering above 75%. - Conversely, most countries with life expectancy over 75 years have significantly lower levels of sanitation deprivation. - This visual supports the idea that public health and basic infrastructure go hand in hand.

Improved sanitation doesnt just reflect progress it helps drive it.

Sanitation Access Over Time: Three Country Case Studies

This line chart compares how sanitation access has evolved over time in:

  • Chad (low-income)
  • Brazil (upper-middle income)
  • Indonesia (middle-income)

Key takeaways: - Brazil shows consistent improvement, reducing sanitation gaps. - Indonesia makes moderate progress, though with occasional stagnation. - Chad shows very limited progress, reflecting structural development challenges.

This comparison illustrates how economic and policy differences shape sanitation outcomes.

Conclusion

Access to sanitation is more than a matter of infrastructure it is a reflection of global inequality, economic capacity, and political will.

This report has highlighted how: - Sanitation access remains critically low in many low-income countries - GDP per capita and life expectancy are strongly correlated with better access - A handful of countries still have over half their population without improved sanitation - Progress over time is uneven, showing that development trajectories matter

No one should be denied a basic human right due to where they were born.
Addressing the sanitation gap requires targeted investment, international cooperation, and prioritizing the needs of the most vulnerable populations.

Achieving SDG 6: Clean Water and Sanitation for All is not only a technical challenge it is a moral imperative.
